{"key":"post-13134399","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>13134399</id>\n<content>If there's only one hole in the bottom, it's serving as a two way street.&amp;nbsp; You're not pulling a vacuum in the container because of CO2 'draining out'.&amp;nbsp; The reason we don't only use one hole in a terrarium is because fresh air is the number one pinning trigger.&amp;nbsp; If we could maintain humidity in open air, that would be the best of all, and it isn't just about CO2.&amp;nbsp; It's about causing evaporation of moisture from the substrate.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;We've all seen the demonstration of CO2 in a glass and how you can pour it on a candle and put the flame out.&amp;nbsp; That's not the principle at work in a mushroom terrarium, or especially in a larger farm such as mine shown below, which is underground and has no 'drainage' provisions at the bottom for release of gasses.&amp;nbsp; Both vents are on the ceiling, and pass upwards 20' to the surface.&amp;nbsp; The results speak for themselves.&amp;nbsp; CO2 levels run around 500ppm to 600ppm during full production, and they're no higher on the bottom shelves than on the top ones.&lt;br /&gt;RR&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://files.shroomery.org/files/10-30/054482710-Mountain_Mushroom_Farm-Shiitake.jpg&quot; class=&quot;highslide&quot; onclick=&quot;return hs.expand(this,{slideshowGroup:'hsg1'})&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;&lt;img style=&quot;max-width:192px;height:auto;&quot; src=&quot;/forums/thumbs/10-30/054482710-thumb_Mountain_Mushroom_Farm-Shiitake.jpg&quot;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>13134538</next>\n<prev>13134357</prev>\n<first>13133566</first>\n<last>13149478</last>\n<when>1283377154</when>\n<utime>09/02/10 12:39 AM</utime>\n</post>"}